Global remittances are projected to reach $774 billion this year and rise further to $810.79 billion by 2023. The Insider Intelligence report, an international publication, in its Global Remittances Forecast 2022, stated that global remittance inflows will grow by 5.9 per cent  this year and 4.7 per cent next year to reach $810.79 billion. Last year, according to the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) diaspora remittances into Nigeria rose to $14.2 billion in the nine months ending September, up 10 per cent from $12.9 billion in the corresponding period of 2020, reflecting the impact of post-COVID economic recovery measures.   Active global airlines fleet to grow by 13% in 2022     Nigeria raises Euro 700m Eurobond to increase finances to…     RMAFC challenges Finance Act in court, insists on autonomy   CBN’s analysis showed that diaspora remittances rose by 5.1 per cent to $4.28 billion in the first quarter of 2021 from $4.07 billion in fourth quarter of 2020. The upward trend continued in second and third quarters, when diaspora remittances rose by 21 per cent and 1.0 per cent to $4.92 billion and $4.97 billion respectively. Analysts expect Nigeria’s yearly diaspora remittances to hit $18 billion, slightly above the $17.6 billion projected by the World Bank. - Advertisement - The  World Bank in a report entitled,  “Migration and Development Brief 35,”  released last November, had projected that Nigeria’s diaspora remittances will increase  2.5 per cent to $17.6 billion in 2021 from $17.2 billion last year. The 10 per cent increase during the nine-month ended September 2021 also represented a reversal of the 41 per cent decline recorded in 2020 when diaspora remittances fell to $16.94 billion from $23.45 billion in 2020 due to the impact of COVID-19 triggered economic lockdown on the incomes of Nigerians in diaspora. SPONSORED